<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08053i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08053i">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08053i"> 53(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ hold pen by end</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Notre exemple de la fig. 94 a besoin d&apos;&ecirc;tre expliqu&eacute;. Il est ordonn&eacute;, calibr&eacute;, nullement h&eacute;sitant. Cela doit suffire &agrave; mettre le graphologue en garde contre une appr&eacute;ciation p&eacute;jorative. Il appartient, en effet, &agrave; un homme de valeur, qui n&apos;est ni d&eacute;bile, ni d&eacute;sagr&eacute;able, bien au contraire. Sous la menace de la crampe des &eacute;crivains il a d&ucirc; adopter cette forme d&apos;&eacute;criture automatique qu&apos;il obtient avec un gros porteplume tenu presque par son extr&eacute;mit&eacute;. <br><font color="green">[Our example of fig. 94 should be explained. It is orderly, calibrated, in no way hesitant. This should be enough to warn a graphologist against a negative evaluation. It does belong to a man of value, who is neither stupid nor disagreeable, but the contrary. Because of writer&apos;s cramp, he has had to adopt this form of automatic writing which is the result of holding a thick pen almost at its end.]</font> <small> J Cr&eacute;pieux-Jamin, <a name="JCJL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JCJL"><cite title="source">Les &eacute;l&eacute;ments de l'&eacute;criture des canailles</cite></a> (1923) 191</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
